          "title": "The defect regulations — symbolic logic and pastoral limits (21:17-23)",
          "body": "The third section is the chapter's most theologically demanding for modern readers. Ten specific physical defects disqualify a descendant of Aaron from approaching the altar to offer (vv. 18-20). The list is comprehensive: visible impairments (blindness, lameness), facial and limb abnormalities (disfigured face, deformed limb, broken foot, broken hand), bodily proportions (hunchback, dwarfism), eye conditions, skin diseases, and genital injury. The key to interpreting this section is the parallel with the sacrificial animal: Leviticus 22:20-21 uses the identical term *mum* (defect) to disqualify blemished animals from altar sacrifice. The priest's body and the animal's body are both instruments of communication in the sacrificial system — they both say something about the God being approached and the adequacy of what is offered. A defective sacrifice would communicate that imperfect gifts satisfy a holy God; a defective officiant would communicate that imperfect mediators can stand in the gap before a holy God. Neither is true. Critically, the defective priest is not expelled from the covenant community or stripped of his priestly identity. He may eat the most holy food and the holy food (v. 22). He is sustained, provided for, included. Only the specific function of drawing near to offer is restricted — and the stated reason is precise: 'so that he will not profane My sanctuaries' (v. 23). The restriction is about the integrity of the sanctuary's visual theology, not about the man's worth before God."
