        "title": "The body as visual theology — defects and the altar (21:17-23)",
        "range": "21:17-23",
        "excerpt": "No man of your offspring throughout their generations who has a defect shall approach to offer the food of his God... He may eat the food of his God, both of the most holy and of the holy, only he shall not go in to the veil or come near the altar because he has a defect, so that he will not profane My sanctuaries.",
        "body": "The third section (vv. 17-23) is the chapter's most exegetically demanding. The list of ten disqualifying defects (vv. 18-20) — ranging from blindness and lameness to skin disease and crushed testicles — is comprehensive and precise. The interpretive key that unlocks the section is the identical terminology used in Leviticus 22:20-25 for disqualifying blemished animals from sacrifice. Both the priest who offers and the animal he offers must be free of *mum* (defect). The parallel is not accidental: it is the chapter's architectural logic. The priestly body is a sign; the sacrificial animal is a sign; both signs must be legible — must communicate without interference the wholeness, completeness, and adequacy that the God being approached possesses and requires.\n\nWenham (NICOT) and Milgrom (Leviticus 17–22, AB) both observe that the defect regulations are not expressions of prejudice against disability but expressions of the typological system's visual grammar. The sanctuary is a place of enacted visual theology — everything about it, from the tabernacle's structure to the priests' garments to the sacrificial animals, is designed to communicate truth about God and about Israel's covenant with Him. A defect in the offering-priest interrupts that visual communication in a way that would, in God's words, 'profane My sanctuaries' (v. 23). Milgrom notes that *chalal* (profane) here carries specifically the sense of 'making the sacred indistinguishable from the common' — which is precisely what an incomplete, visually impaired priest at the altar would do.\n\nThe pastoral provision of verse 22 is crucial and often overlooked in discussions of this section. The defective priest may eat of the most holy food and the holy food — the highest categories of priestly portions. He is not expelled from the covenant, stripped of his lineage, or denied sustenance. He receives what Aaron's sons receive. He participates in the covenant provision. Only the specific act of approaching the veil and the altar to offer is barred. The restriction is functional and symbolic, not personal and condemnatory.\n\nReformed commentators (Calvin, Matthew Henry) have generally read this section as pointing forward to the perfect offering of Christ — who, as both priest and sacrifice, was required to be without blemish. Hebrews 9:14 describes Jesus offering Himself 'without blemish to God' — the same requirement that governed both the Levitical animals (*mum*-free) and the Levitical priests (*mum*-free). The defect regulations in Leviticus 21 are not abolished by the New Testament; they are transcended by the one mediator who satisfied them perfectly. As John Owen writes in his commentary on Hebrews, 'the imperfections of the Levitical priesthood were not accidental features but were designed by God to drive Israel's faith forward to the priest who would be without defect, without end, and without the need of repetition.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mum* (defect, blemish) appears five times in this section (vv. 17, 18, 21 ×2, 23) — the same term used for disqualifying animal sacrifices (Lev 22:20-21; Deut 15:21; 17:1; Num 19:2). *Miqdash* (sanctuary, vv. 12, 23) — derived from *qadash*, to sanctify; God's possessive 'My sanctuaries' (*miqdashay*) at v. 23 is the chapter's final and most comprehensive territorial claim."
