        "number": 4,
        "title": "The divine name as the ground of all regulation — 'I am the LORD who sanctifies'",
        "range": "21:8, 12, 15, 23",
        "excerpt": "For I the Lord, who sanctifies you, am holy... I am the LORD... For I am the LORD who sanctifies him... For I am the LORD who sanctifies them.",
        "body": "The four occurrences of the divine self-declaration in Leviticus 21 are not decorative closings; they are the chapter's theological argument in compressed form. Each is a first-person divine speech act: God asserting who He is as the ground of what He requires. This formula — appearing throughout Leviticus (18:5, 6, 21, 30; 19:3, 4, 10, 12, 14, etc.) — has its roots in the covenant declaration of Exodus 6:2-8, where God reveals His name to Moses as the basis of His redemptive acts. 'I am the LORD' is always both a credential and a claim: this is who I am, and therefore this is what I require.\n\nThe progression through the chapter's three sections is theologically deliberate. At verse 8, the formula is applied to the congregation's obligation toward the priest: the people must regard the priest as holy *because* God — the one who sanctifies — has already sanctified him. The obligation is grounded in a prior divine act. At verse 12, the bare 'I am the LORD' closes the high-priestly mourning prohibition — no elaboration is needed; the divine name is sufficient authority. At verse 15, the sanctifying activity is applied specifically to the high priest (*him*). At verse 23, the object widens to the sanctuaries themselves (*them*) — God's ownership of the sacred spaces is the final word in the chapter's argument.\n\nThe progression can be read as moving from persons to spaces: God sanctifies the congregation (implicitly, v. 8), the high priest (v. 15), and the sanctuaries (v. 23). The entire visible architecture of Israelite worship — people, priests, and place — is brought under the single claim of the divine name. Nothing in the system exists independently; everything derives its sacred status from the God who says 'I am the LORD who sanctifies.'\n\nThis has direct canonical bearing on the New Testament's treatment of holiness. When Paul declares 'you are not your own; you were bought with a price. Therefore glorify God in your body' (1 Corinthians 6:19-20), the logic is structurally identical to Leviticus 21's: the divine act of claiming (purchasing, in Paul; sanctifying, in Leviticus) is the ground of the human obligation. Keller (Center Church) observes that the gospel does not abandon Leviticus's logic of divine-claim-grounding-human-obligation; it deepens it — not oil on a priest's head but the blood of the Son on the altar of the cross establishes the new covenant community as God's holy possession.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** The formula *ani Yhwh mekadishkhem* (I am the LORD who sanctifies you/him/them) uses the *piel* participle of *qadash* — indicating ongoing, intensive, causative action. God does not merely declare the priest holy once; He is continuously in the act of setting apart. The participial form ('who sanctifies,' not 'who sanctified') is theologically important: the sanctification is not merely historical but perpetual."
